The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, Dec. 25: Days after the passage of the US legislation on civil nuclear cooperation with India, Bharat Heavy Electricals is in talks with global players, such as GE and Siemens, and may invest up to Rs 500 crore to expand its nuclear production capacities. Our primary objective is technology tieup, but we are not averse to forming a joint venture, Bhel chairman and managing director Ashok K. Puri said.

 New Delhi, Dec. 25: Global companies, including Mitsui Chemicals and Mitsubishi Chemical Corporation, are eyeing a stake in Oil and Natural Gas Corporations Rs 13,600-crore petrochemical complex at Dahej in Gujarat. The company plans to get a strategic partner in the project next year.

 New Delhi, Dec. 25: Infosys is in talks with 10 international banks for its universal core banking solution Finacle. Finacles revenues from exports are nearly 69 per cent of the total revenue. It faces stiff competition from i-flexs Flexcube and Switzerlands Taminos.

 Mumbai, Dec. 25: Lotus India Mutual Fund, a joint venture between Singapore-based Fullerton Fund Management and Sabre Capital Worldwide, may buy an asset management company, but denied that Standard Chartered could be a target. 

 New Delhi, Dec. 25: Nasscom has tied up with Canada-based Data Wind Corporation to provide Internet connectivity in rural areas. The two companies have begun a pilot project in Orissa, Andhra Pradesh, Bengal and Maharashtra.




